#Tree:
#A Tree is a non-linear data structure made up of nodes connected by edges. It has one root node and no cycles.

#Binary Tree:
#A Binary Tree is a tree in which each node can have at most two children: left child and right child.

#Binary Search Tree (BST)
#A Binary Search Tree is a binary tree where:
#Left subtree values are less than the root.
#Right subtree values are greater than the root.

#Complete Binary Tree:
#A Complete Binary Tree is a binary tree where:
#All levels are completely filled except possibly the last level.
#Nodes in the last level are filled from left to right.

#Min Heap
#A Min Heap is a complete binary tree where the parent node is smaller than or equal to its children.

#Max Heap
#A Max Heap is a complete binary tree where the parent node is greater than or equal to its children.

#HEAP:
#A Heap is a complete binary tree in which the value node is either greater than,less than,or equal to the value
in child node is called a Heap

#difference between Array and lined list:
| Array                                | Linked List                              |
| ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| Stores elements in contiguous memory | Stores elements in non-contiguous memory |
| Fast access using index              | Sequential access                        |
| Fixed size (generally)               | Dynamic size                             |
| Insertion/deletion is costly         | Insertion/deletion is easier             |

#Difference Between DFS and BFS:
| DFS                  | BFS                     |
| -------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Depth First Search   | Breadth First Search    |
| Explores depth first | Explores level by level |
| Uses Stack/Recursion | Uses Queue              |
| Less memory          | More memory             |


#What is Hashing?
Hashing is a technique used to store and retrieve data efficiently by 
converting a key into an index using a hash function.
        Example:
        Key = 18
        Hash Function = key % 6
        18 % 6 = 0

#A good interview answer if asked "How do you find time complexity?" is:
"I count how many times the main operation executes. Single loops usually give O(n), 
nested loops multiply to O(n²) or O(n³), and when the input is repeatedly halved, the complexity is O(log n).
 If a loop contains a halving operation, it becomes O(n log n)."
 

